Of the 24 participants, 7 were male and 17 were female. We provide the average age, disease duration, baseline BAI score, and finger temperature in Table 1
. Analysis with the chi-square and Mann-Whitney U tests revealed no statistically significant differences in these variables between the two groups (Table 1). Analysis using the chi-square test also showed no statistically significant differences between the two groups with respect to comorbid conditions (Table 2
).

The experimental group had an increase of mean relative alpha EEG percentage from 38.1% to 46.7% from preintervention to postintervention session for all sessions combined, with mean increases of 5.1, 8.8, 5.1, 7.3, and 8.6 percentage points at 5, 10, 15, 20, and 25 min, respectively (Figure 3
). Mean change in alpha EEG differed significantly between the experimental and control groups for 5 of the 11 study sessions. The Mann-Whitney U test showed a statistically significant difference between the 2 groups in the 11 combined sessions after the intervention (U = −3.36, p = .0004; Table 4
). Alpha EEG percentage in the experimental group not only increased significantly during music therapy but also was higher than that in the control group postintervention session (Figure 3).
